{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.56,0.09,0.1,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1222"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57968"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"10994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a one day history of feeling unwell, with fevers, rigors and pain in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen. One year ago she underwent a gastric bypass procedure for morbid obesity. She has managed to lose 35 kg since the surgery. She has not had any other surgical procedures. Her previously diagnosed type 2 diabetes does not now need any medication and her hypertension has resolved. The only medication she takes is simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her sclera are icteric, pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the right upper quadrant. Bloods are taken for routine haematological and biochemical analysis and blood cultures are also performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic bile duct exploration","Ultrasound","CT abdomen","MRCP","ERCP"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient almost certainly has cholangitis and usual cause will be gallstones. The focus must be on her sepsis and getting that under control before looking for the cause. Blood cultures have been taken and the patient with need intravenous fluids and antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce her condition has been stabilised, investigations can be undertaken to determine the underlying cause. This patient has lost weight rapidly after her recent bariatric surgery and this is an important contributory factor to the development of gallstones. In this clinical situation the preferred investigation will be \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a simple and cheap investigation, with a 95% sensitivity in the detection of gallstones. The sensitivity for common bile ducts falls to about 40% - but that is of less importance if the ultrasound can pick up stones in the gallbladder and a dilated common bile duct. By inference, such latter findings will strongly support the diagnosis of a stone in the common bile duct. The aim of this investigation is to:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eidentify gallstones - particularly in the common bile duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eidentify any dilatation of the biliary tree\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst some form of intervention may be required to decompress the common bile duct, an ERCP is not likely to be the procedure of choice - the patient has had a previous Roux-en-Y gastric bypass for her morbid obesity. MRCP is increasingly used in the assessment of biliary pathology and may have a secondary role in the management of this case. CT is less sensitive in the detection of gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The incidence of gallstone formation is increased in patients who have undergone rapid weight loss - such as with bariatric surgery."],"references":["Gurusamy KS, Davidson BR. Gallstones. BMJ 2014; 348:g2669. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24755732/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57968"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57968"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T21:30:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-28T20:13:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1222"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"